node.text:
💧 With Hubble data, astronomers found evidence of water vapor in the atmosphere of Jupiter’s moon Ganymede!

This is an ice-covered world that might hold more water than all of Earth’s oceans combined… but Ganymede’s oceans exist below a 100-mile-thick, icy crust.

This atmospheric water vapor was formed in a process called sublimation, when a solid turns directly into a gas (ice ➡️ water vapor).

Find out more about this discovery at the link in our bio!

#NASA #Hubble #video #Jupiter #Ganymede #moon #planet #space #solarsystem #water #news

node.title: Hubble Finds Evidence of Water Vapor at Jupiter’s Moon Ganymede

“That’s one of the benefits of a program that’s been running for over 30 years: the incredible amount of experience and expertise.”

After Hubble ran into a payload computer issue on June 13, team members new and old worked to recover the telescope. Science operations resumed on July 17.

Their efforts helped ensure that Hubble’s exploration of the universe is far from over. Read more at the link in our bio!

Dark matter is the “invisible glue” that holds the universe together.

All galaxies seem to be dominated by it, but Hubble observations of an oddball galaxy lacking dark matter are challenging theories of galaxy formation.

Learn more about this cosmic mystery at the link in our bio!

This planet may have lost one atmosphere, but gained another!

Hubble studied an exoplanet (a planet outside our solar system) 41 light-years away. Its original atmosphere is believed to have been lost due to the intense radiation of the star it orbits, but this rocky exoplanet might have a second one through volcanic activity.

What exactly is a “deep field” image?

These mesmerizing images aren’t just beautiful to look at – we can discover so much about the history of our universe, too!

In this video, learn more about what we’re seeing when we look at a deep field.

node.text:
Welcome to #DeepFieldWeek! 

This picture changed everything. Since the original Hubble deep field image was taken in 1995, our understanding of the universe and our place within it has never been the same.

Throughout this week, we'll be sharing exciting content about Hubble’s iconic deep field images, which revolutionized our perception of the cosmos.

Hubble deep fields are long-exposure images of relatively “empty” patches in the sky, giving us an astonishing glimpse into the magnitude of our universe and allowing us to see far back in time to some of the earliest galaxies. Some combine long-exposures with nature’s own magnifying lens, a phenomena known as gravitational lensing, so we can see even more detail!

Join us each day as we take a “deep” dive into the history, legacy, and future of these images that helped shape astronomy. Learn more at the link in our bio!

P.S.: Wondering what’s up with the “blank” portions in the top right? A previous camera installed on Hubble, called the Wide Field and Planetary Camera 2, produced a “step” effect. The dark regions are just portions that have no Hubble data. Three of the camera’s four light detectors imaged “wide fields,” while the fourth detector had higher resolution but covered a smaller portion of the sky.

Image credits: R. Williams (STScI), the Hubble Deep Field Team and NASA

#nasa #hubble #astronomy #science

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Hubble Space Telescope on July 30, 2021.

node.text:
Galactic siblings fight, too.

This #HubbleFriday view shows a triplet of galaxies, called Arp 195, caught in a gravitational tug-of-war game.

Ask any astronomer, and they’ll tell you that observation time with Hubble is extremely valuable.

There isn’t time to waste a second, so the schedule for Hubble’s observations is calculated using a computer algorithm which allows the spacecraft to sometimes collect “bonus” snapshots of data in between longer observations.

This image is one of those “extra” observations! Beyond providing spectacular images, these observations can help identify promising targets to follow up with using telescopes like @nasawebb! 

For more information, visit the link in our bio.

Image credits: ESA/Hubble & NASA, J. Dalcanton

#NASA #Hubble #Friday #galaxy #siblings #gravity #space #science #astronomy

📍 Welcome to Mystic Mountain!

The Carina Nebula, located 7,500 light-years away in the southern constellation Carina, is a massive star-forming region in the Milky Way Galaxy. 

Gas in the nebula is eroded away by high-energy radiation emitted from young stars. When dense pockets of gas resist the erosion, giant pillars are formed housing new stars buried deep within the cloud. 

This visualization brings the Hubble image to life, showcasing different stars and layers of the nebula distributed across space. 

Visualization credits: NASA, G. Bacon, L. Frattare, Z. Levay, and F. Summers (STScI/AURA)

Music credit: “Space Flight,” Stuart Thomas [PRS], Abbey Road Masters, Universal Production Music

Welcome to the core of Caldwell 108!

This spherical, dense group of stars (called a globular cluster) contains both old and new members, and is located about 19,000 light-years away.

Curious about the “missing” strip through the middle? Hubble’s Wide Field Camera 3 uses two detectors that are near but not exactly next to each other, leaving a thin gap in the exposure. This image was taken to prove that a new method of using Hubble’s gyroscopes (developed to extend their lifetime) would still produce the high-quality science observations Hubble is known for.

Image credits: Credits: NASA, ESA, and M. Reinhart (STScI); Processing: Gladys Kober (NASA/Catholic University of America)

💧 With Hubble data, astronomers found evidence of water vapor in the atmosphere of Jupiter’s moon Ganymede!

This is an ice-covered world that might hold more water than all of Earth’s oceans combined… but Ganymede’s oceans exist below a 100-mile-thick, icy crust.

This atmospheric water vapor was formed in a process called sublimation, when a solid turns directly into a gas (ice ➡️ water vapor).

Find out more about this discovery at the link in our bio!

Take a look through this cosmic lens 🔎

Gravitational lensing is like nature’s magnifying glass. It can warp or magnify the appearance of distant galaxies due to a huge gravitational pull from an astronomical object in between it and the viewer!

This phenomenon is on full display in this #HubbleFriday view of a galaxy cluster, with gravitational lensing’s tell-tale arcs framing the image’s center.

Read more at the link in our bio!

Image credits: ESA/Hubble & NASA, A. Newman, M. Akhshik, K. Whitaker

node.text:
It takes a team!

Go behind the scenes to Hubble's control center, where the Hubble team completed a successful switch to backup hardware on the telescope last week.

Thanks to them, Hubble is back to work, furthering our understanding of the universe.

Find out more about the team’s work in restoring Hubble at the link in our bio.

Image credit: Rebecca Roth

1) Anomaly Response Manager Nzinga Tull monitors the results of operations procedures as they are executed to switch the spacecraft to backup hardware.

2) The Space Telescope Operations Control Center as seen from behind the NASA Operations Manager station as the Hubble team works on switching to backup hardware.

3) System engineering manager Dan Smith discusses preparations for returning the spacecraft control from a special-purpose safe mode computer to its main computer. The main computer that normally controls the spacecraft had to be turned off during the switch to backup hardware.

4) While the spacecraft is controlled by a special-purpose safe mode computer, a subsystem engineer monitors Hubble’s pointing control subsystem, which is used to turn and steady Hubble. The main computer that normally controls the spacecraft had to be turned off during the switch to backup hardware.

5) NASA Operation Manager (NOM) Dave Haskins makes a phone call to brief project management on progress with the switch to backup hardware, while two other NOMs, Dr. Olivia Lupie and Mike Myslinski, discuss the current activity in the background. Due to pandemic precautions, a core team was present in the control center while the remainder of the team monitored and supported from home.

6) Senior system engineers discuss a “memory dump” of the main computer, in which the contents are sent to the ground to verify everything is loaded and functioning properly.

7) Experts on the Hubble subsystem, which turns the spacecraft from one target to the next and keeps it steady for taking images, discuss a future pointing maneuver that will be done during the day’s activities.
